<article id="node-17030">
<h1 >3.4.10.70 Total Net Value of Sugarcane Farms for RASF</h1>
<p><strong>Note:</strong> THIS SCHEME CLOSED on 12 July 2007 and the following INFORMATION is FOR HISTORICAL PURPOSES ONLY.</p>
<h2>Summary</h2>
<p>Participation in <a href="../../../acronyms#rasf" title="Retirement assistance for sugarcane farmers scheme">RASF</a> is limited to sugarcane farmers, their partners or former partners who have ownership of a sugarcane farm/s (<a href="../../../1/1/s/405">1.1.S.405</a>) and farm assets worth up to $500,000. This topic explains the issues surrounding the valuation of the sugarcane farm/s and relevant sugar cane farm assets.</p>
<h2>What is the net farm value?</h2>
<p>The total net value of the sugarcane farm/s and relevant sugarcane farm assets is the aggregate of all sugarcane farm assets and liabilities.</p>
<p>Sugarcane farm debts are only money borrowed for the purposes of a sugarcane farm and can only be counted as debt if it has not been repaid before the transfer of the farm. If the sugarcane farm is mortgaged to borrow money for a non-sugarcane purpose (e.g. a holiday home), then this debt should not be included as sugarcane farm debt when calculating the farm's net value. Where the farmer has significant off-farm assets, the purpose of previous borrowing against the farm needs to be verified by requesting loan application from the farmer's lending institution.</p>
<p><strong>Exceptions:</strong> The market value of the house and curtilage (<a href="../../../1/1/a/58">1.1.A.58</a>) does NOT count toward the total value, IF the farmer retains a life, freehold or leasehold interest in it.</p>
<div class="example">
<p>Example: A person who has a pastoral lease on a farm will not be able to hold a life interest in the farmhouse and curtilage. However, they will be able to hold a leasehold interest in the farmhouse and curtilage from the eligible descendant.</p>
</div>
<p>If the descendant already has an eligible interest (<a href="../../../1/1/e/75">1.1.E.75</a>) in the farm, then the value of that interest is also disregarded from the total farm value.</p>
<p>These points are explained in the rest of this topic.</p>
<h2>The $500,000 limit</h2>
<p>The $500,000 limit applies to the combined value of ALL sugarcane farms in which the farmer has a qualifying interest, NOT each farm. This includes the total value of sugarcane farm enterprises where the farmer is in partnership (<a href="../../../1/1/p/95">1.1.P.95</a>).</p>
<div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A farmer owns a $300,000 sugarcane property outright, and is also a 50% partner in another sugarcane property valued at $280,000. This farmer therefore has a qualifying interest in sugarcane farm assets that exceed the $500,000 limit.</p>
</div>
<p>Different provisions apply however if the eligible descendant/s already has a qualifying interest in the farm or farm assets. These provisions are explained in the referenced topic.</p>
<p>The limit applies to the following, regardless of how many farms are involved:</p>
<ul><li>the qualifying sugarcane farmer (<a href="../../../1/1/q/50">1.1.Q.50</a>), OR</li>
<li>the qualifying farmer and their partner, OR</li>
<li>the former partner of a qualifying farmer, OR</li>
<li>a group of retiring farmers who are partners in a farm (see example).</li>
</ul><div class="example">
<p><strong>Example:</strong> A sugarcane farm enterprise valued at $700,000 is owned by 2 brothers, each owning a half share valued at $350,000. In this case, the retiring farmer cannot qualify for RASF.</p>
</div>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="90">3.4.10.90</a> RASF - Descendant Already has Part Ownership</p>
</div>
<h2>Valuations</h2>
<p>The farmland will need to be valued by the Australian Valuation Office unless:</p>
<ul><li>there is a recent valuation on file, OR</li>
<li>the applicant has provided a valuation by a registered, independent, professional valuer.</li>
</ul><p>The farming assets, for example, plant, machinery, etc should be valued at book value as shown on the most recent balance sheet for the farm business. There is no requirement to obtain an Australian Valuation Office valuation of these assets.</p>
<p>The delegate must be convinced that any independent valuation of the farm is done at market value (i.e. not forced sale or mortgage borrowing value - both of which are likely to be lower than market value). If there is any doubt, an opinion from the Australian Valuation Office should be sought as validation.</p>
<div class="reference">
<p><strong>Policy reference:</strong> SS Guide <a href="../../../4/6/6">4.6.6</a> Determining the Value of an Asset</p>
</div>
